# Rails 8+ Project -- Claude Code Instructions

## Identity

You are working on a production Rails 8+ application. Follow modern Rails best
practices (2025+) using Hotwire (Turbo + Stimulus), the Solid Trio (Queue,
Cache, Cable), and DHH-style coding conventions. Write clean, idiomatic Ruby.
Prioritize correctness, readability, and security. Do not over-engineer.

---

## Output and Efficiency

<!-- Adapted from https://github.com/drona23/claude-token-efficient -->

### Response Style

- Return code first. Explanation after, only if non-obvious.
- No sycophantic openers or closing fluff. Do not restate the question.
- No unsolicited suggestions beyond the requested scope.
- Be concise in output but thorough in reasoning.
- Use comments sparingly -- only where logic is unclear.

### Work Efficiency

- Read before writing. One focused coding pass. No write-delete-rewrite cycles.
- Do not re-read files already read unless they may have changed.
- If unsure: say so. Never guess or invent file paths, class names, or APIs.
- User instructions always override this file.

### Token Efficiency

- Targeted reads (offset/limit) over full-file reads. Use Grep/Glob for search.
- Batch independent tool calls in parallel. Prefer Edit over Write.
- Show only changed code blocks when explaining fixes.
- Omit requires the reader can infer from existing patterns.
- Keep explanations to one or two sentences. Skip if code is self-explanatory.
- Budget: 50 tool calls maximum per task.

### ASCII Output

- No em dashes, smart quotes, or Unicode bullets in code output.
- Plain hyphens and straight quotes only. Copy-paste safe.

### Code Review Behavior

- State the bug. Show the fix. Stop. No compliments, no out-of-scope suggestions.

### Debugging Behavior

- Never speculate without reading the relevant code first.
- State what you found, where, and the fix. One pass. If cause is unclear: say so.

---

## Ruby Style and Code Quality Rules

### General

- Simplest code that solves the problem. Minimal runtime cost.
- One class or module per file. CamelCase class names. Files under 200 lines.
- Only comment non-obvious "why" -- never "what". Remove dead code; do not comment it out.
- `frozen_string_literal: true` magic comment at the top of every Ruby file.
- Double quotes by default. Single quotes only when the string contains a contraction or backslash escapes you want literal.
- No speculative features. No abstractions for single-use operations.
- Three similar lines is better than a premature abstraction.
- Prefer plain Ruby over gems when the problem fits in 20 lines. DHH's omakase philosophy: trust Rails, trust Ruby, reach for dependencies last.

### Conditionals

- Prefer expanded conditionals over guard clauses for anything beyond a trivial early-exit. Expanded `if/else` reads top-to-bottom without forcing readers to hold state.
- Exception: a single guard clause at the very start of a method is fine when the body that follows is non-trivial.
- Use assignment-in-condition when it makes intent clearer: `if user = User.find_by(...)`.

### Method Ordering

- Class methods first (`self.xxx`), then public instance methods, then private.
- Within a visibility block, order private methods by the sequence in which public methods call them. Readers should follow call flow top-to-bottom.

### Visibility Modifiers

- No blank line between `private` and the methods beneath it.
- Indent method definitions under `private` by two spaces (visibility as a visual scope).
- Exception: if a module contains only private methods, place `private` at the top with a blank line after it and do NOT indent.

### Bang Methods

- Only use `!` on methods that have a non-bang counterpart (`save`/`save!`, `create`/`create!`).
- Do not tack `!` onto a method name just to signal destructiveness.

### Blocks and Enumerables

- Use `.each` when you do not need the return value. Use `.map` only when the result is used.
- Prefer `.find`, `.select`, `.reject`, `.any?`, `.all?`, `.none?` over hand-rolled loops.
- `.find_each` for record batches (see Section 6).

### Value Objects

- Use `Data.define(:a, :b)` (Ruby 3.2+) or `Struct.new(:a, :b)` for simple immutable value holders.
- Promote to a full class when you need validation, defaults, or methods.

---

## Controller Rules

### REST Purity

- Model every endpoint as a CRUD operation on a resource.
- If an action doesn't map cleanly to `index/show/new/create/edit/update/destroy`, create a new resource instead of adding custom actions. Example: `resource :closure, only: [:create, :destroy]` instead of `post :close` / `post :reopen` on the parent.
- Never add verbs like `post :close` or `post :approve` to an existing controller.

### Thin Controllers

- Controllers set up instance variables, call a model method, and render. That's it.
- Business logic lives in models and model concerns, not controllers. If a controller action grows beyond ~10 lines, you're probably missing a model method.
- No service objects by default. Business logic on models + concerns. See Section 13 for when a service might be justified.

### Strong Params

- Always whitelist with `params.expect` (Rails 8+) or `params.require(...).permit(...)`.
- Define a private `<resource>_params` method at the bottom of the controller.
- `params.expect` raises `ActionController::ParameterMissing` on shape mismatches. Prefer it over `permit`.

### Before Actions and Concerns

- Use `before_action` for setup: loading records, checking permissions, scoping to `Current`.
- Extract shared behavior into concerns under `app/controllers/concerns/`.
- Skip with `skip_before_action` judiciously. Prefer declarative class methods (e.g. `allow_unauthenticated_access only: :new`) over ad-hoc skips.
- The `Authentication` concern should provide `authenticated?`, `current_user`, `require_authentication`, and `allow_unauthenticated_access`.

### Responses

- Use `head :status_code` for responses without a body: `head :forbidden`, `head :no_content`.
- Return the right status on failed writes: `render :new, status: :unprocessable_entity`.
- Turbo relies on `:unprocessable_entity` to re-render forms in place.

---

## Model Rules

### Rich Models

- Put business logic in models and model concerns, not controllers or service objects.
- Keep the main model file under ~100 lines. If it's growing past that, extract concerns.

### Concerns

- Model concerns live in `app/models/concerns/` for cross-cutting behavior or in `app/models/<model>/` for model-specific aspects.
- Include concerns alphabetically in the class body.
- One concern, one responsibility.
- Module name matches file path: `User::Authentication` lives at `app/models/user/authentication.rb`.

### Modern ActiveRecord Features

- `has_secure_password` for password hashing (bcrypt included).
- `normalizes :attr, with: ->(v) { v.strip.downcase }` for auto-normalizing (emails, phone numbers).
- `encrypts :attr` for column-level encryption (AES-256-GCM by default).
- `generates_token_for :purpose, expires_in: 15.minutes { record.password_salt.last(10) }` for signed, scoped, time-limited tokens. Use for password resets, email confirmation, magic links.
- Enums with `prefix: true` to avoid method-name collisions: `enum :status, { draft: 0, published: 1 }, prefix: true` produces `status_draft?` / `status_published?`.

### Defaults and Delegation

- Use lambda defaults on associations: `belongs_to :creator, default: -> { Current.user }`.
- Use `delegate` to avoid repetitive getter chains: `delegate :name, :email, to: :user, prefix: true`.

### Validations

- Validate what the database cannot enforce: business rules, format, presence, uniqueness (paired with a unique index).
- Use custom validator classes for complex rules that repeat across models.

---

## ActiveRecord and Query Rules

### Associations

- `inverse_of` on bidirectional associations. Prevents N+1 when traversing the graph in memory.
- `touch: true` on `belongs_to` when parent cache keys should bust on child updates.
- `counter_cache: true` to cache counts without a COUNT query.
- `dependent: :destroy` or `dependent: :delete_all` or `dependent: :nullify` -- pick one explicitly. Never leave orphans.

### N+1 Prevention

- Use `includes(:association)` when you'll touch the association on each record.
- Use `preload(:association)` when you don't need the association in the SQL WHERE clause.
- Use `eager_load(:association)` when you do (it generates a LEFT OUTER JOIN).
- Enable `strict_loading` in development to catch N+1 early.

### Query Idioms

- `exists?` instead of `present?` when checking "is there any record" -- `exists?` runs `SELECT 1 LIMIT 1`; `present?` loads the full relation.
- `pluck(:column)` when you only need one or two columns as plain Ruby.
- `where.missing(:association)` for "has no associated record".
- `where.associated(:association)` for the inverse.
- Prefer `size` over `count` when the relation is already loaded.

### Batching

- Use `find_each` to iterate large datasets without loading them all into memory.
- Set `batch_size:` if the default (1,000) is too large for your row shape.

### Bulk Writes

- `insert_all` and `upsert_all` for bulk inserts. They skip callbacks and validations -- useful for speed, dangerous when you rely on callbacks.
- `update_all` for bulk updates that deliberately skip callbacks.
- For large backfills, wrap in `find_each` + `transaction` batches.

### Scopes

- Prefer scopes over class methods for query fragments. Scopes compose and chain naturally.
- Name scopes by intent, not mechanism: `scope :recent` not `scope :ordered_by_created_at_desc`.

### Transactions

- Wrap related writes in `transaction do ... end` so partial failures roll back.
- Never enqueue jobs or call external services inside a transaction (see Section 7).

---

## Callback and Job Rules

### Lambda Callback Syntax (MANDATORY)

- **ALWAYS** use lambda syntax for callbacks: `after_save -> { board.touch }`.
- **NEVER** use symbol syntax: `after_save :touch_board`.
- The lambda shows at the call site exactly what runs, eliminates named-method indirection, and makes callback ordering greppable.

### Commit Callbacks for Async Work (MANDATORY)

- Use `after_create_commit`, `after_update_commit`, `after_save_commit`, `after_destroy_commit` for anything that enqueues a job, calls an external API, broadcasts over Turbo, or has side effects outside the database.
- Plain `after_create` / `after_save` run inside the transaction. Enqueuing from there races (worker reads before commit) and causes lock contention on single-writer databases.
- Plain `before_*` and `after_*` (non-commit) callbacks are fine for synchronous in-transaction work: setting defaults, computing derived attributes, validating data shape.

### The `_later` / `_now` Pair

- When a model method enqueues a job, name it `<verb>_later` and add a sibling `<verb>_now` that does the synchronous work.
- The job's `perform` is a one-liner that calls `<verb>_now`.
- This keeps jobs as shallow wrappers, lets you call the synchronous path from tests and rake tasks, and makes the async/sync split obvious.

### Jobs Are Shallow Wrappers

- Jobs contain no business logic. They unwrap arguments and call a model method.
- All the real work lives on the model, where it's testable without the job runner.

### Retry and Discard

- `retry_on` for transient failures with exponential backoff: `retry_on Net::OpenTimeout, wait: :polynomially_longer, attempts: 5`.
- `discard_on` for permanent failures: `discard_on ActiveRecord::RecordNotFound`.
- Let everything else bubble so Solid Queue records the failure.

### Recurring Tasks

- Define scheduled jobs in `config/recurring.yml` (Solid Queue's native format). No `whenever` gem, no cron.

---

## Hotwire Rules (Turbo and Stimulus)

### Turbo Frames

- Use `turbo_frame_tag` to scope independently refreshable regions of a page.
- Set `loading: "lazy"` on frames whose content is expensive or below the fold.
- Never style the `<turbo-frame>` element directly -- style content inside it.
- Use `target: "_top"` when a link inside a frame should break out and load the full page.

### Turbo Streams and Broadcasts

- Subscribe to broadcasts with `turbo_stream_from Current.user, "channel_name"` in the view.
- Emit broadcasts from `*_commit` callbacks on the model (never from plain `after_*`).
- Scope broadcasts to the current user or account to avoid cross-tenant leaks.
- Use `broadcast_append_to`, `broadcast_replace_to`, `broadcast_remove_to` helpers on the model.

### Server-Rendered HTML Only

- Never generate HTML in JavaScript. If you need new markup on the client, fetch a rendered partial from the server.
- This keeps views themeable from one place, keeps Rails helpers authoritative, and lets system tests exercise real markup.

### Stimulus Controllers

- One controller per file, named by function: `auto_save_controller.js`, `clipboard_controller.js`.
- Declare `static targets`, `static values`, `static outlets`, `static classes` at the top.
- Use private class fields (`#field`) for internal state.
- Organize methods into three sections: **Lifecycle**, **Actions**, **Private**.

### Native `<dialog>` for Modals

- Use the HTML `<dialog>` element with `showModal()`. Do not roll your own overlay div.
- Close on Escape is built in. Close on backdrop click via a small Stimulus action.

---

## View and ERB Rules

### Partials

- Extract repeated markup into partials. Render collections with `render @items` or `render partial: "item", collection: @items`.
- Rails uses the model's `to_partial_path` -- `render @post` finds `app/views/posts/_post.html.erb` automatically.

### DOM IDs and Classes

- Use `dom_id(@post)` and `dom_class(@post)` for stable, conventional ids. They match the patterns `broadcast_*_to` emits.

### Tag Helpers

- Use `tag.div`, `tag.p`, `tag.a` builders rather than string-concatenated HTML.
- `link_to` for navigation, `button_to` for state-changing actions (POST/PATCH/DELETE).

### HTML Safety

- **Never** call `.html_safe` on user input. It disables escaping and opens XSS.
- Use `sanitize(user_html, tags: %w[p a em strong], attributes: %w[href])` when you need to allow a limited HTML subset.
- Prefer rendering user content with plain `<%= %>` and letting Rails escape by default.

### I18n-Ready Strings

- Use `t(".key")` for user-visible strings. Lazy lookup resolves against the view path automatically.
- Use `number_to_currency`, `number_with_delimiter`, `time_ago_in_words` instead of hand-rolled formatters.

### No Inline JavaScript

- Never `<script>` blocks in ERB. Attach behavior via Stimulus `data-controller` / `data-action`.

---

## Error Handling Rules

### Rescue Specific Exceptions

- Never `rescue => e`. That catches everything including `SystemExit` and `NoMemoryError`.
- `rescue StandardError => e` is acceptable as a last-resort catch-all, but only at the top of a job or background worker.
- Use specific exception classes and log with context before re-raising or handling.

### `rescue_from` for HTTP Responses

- Handle `ActiveRecord::RecordNotFound` (404), `ActionController::ParameterMissing` (400), and other common exceptions at the controller level with `rescue_from`.

### Never Swallow Errors

- If you catch an exception, either log it with context or re-raise. Never return `nil` silently.
- Use `Rails.error.report(exception, context: { ... })` for observability integrations.

---

## Performance and Caching Rules

### Fragment Caching

- Cache view fragments on a model: `<% cache @post do %> ... <% end %>`. The cache key auto-expires on `@post.updated_at`.
- Russian-doll: nested caches invalidate naturally via `touch: true`.
- Cache collections with `cached: true` on the `render partial:` call.

### Low-Level Caching

- `Rails.cache.fetch(key, expires_in: 1.hour) { expensive_computation }` for server-side memoization.
- Solid Cache is the default store in Rails 8 -- no Redis needed.

### Counter Caches

- Use `counter_cache: true` on `belongs_to` to keep an association count denormalized on the parent.

### Indexes

- Index every foreign key. Index every column you filter or sort by. Add composite indexes for multi-column queries.
- Add indexes in the same migration that adds the column.

### Lean Queries

- `pluck` for one or two columns. `select` for a subset of columns as real records.
- Prefer `size` on loaded relations and `count` on unloaded.

---

## Security and Authentication Rules (Non-Negotiable)

### Rails 8 Authentication Generator

- Use `bin/rails generate authentication` to scaffold `User` + `Session` models with `has_secure_password`. No Devise.
- Session lives in a database row; a signed cookie carries the session id.
- Cookies must be `httponly`, `secure` in production, and `same_site: :lax`.

### The `Current` Attributes Pattern

- Keep per-request state in `Current < ActiveSupport::CurrentAttributes`. Set it once in `ApplicationController`, read it anywhere.
- Always scope queries through `Current.user` (or `Current.account`). Never `Model.find(params[:id])` on records that belong to a user -- that leaks data.

### CSRF, CSP, and Forgery Protection

- `protect_from_forgery` is enabled by default. Do not disable.
- Configure CSP in `config/initializers/content_security_policy.rb`. Whitelist sources explicitly. Never allow `unsafe-inline` for scripts in production.
- Use nonce-based CSP for inline scripts when absolutely necessary.

### Encrypted Credentials

- Secrets go in `rails credentials:edit`. Access via `Rails.application.credentials.stripe.secret_key`.
- Never commit `master.key` or unencrypted files with secrets.

### Modern Browser Enforcement

- `allow_browser versions: :modern` in `ApplicationController` to drop legacy browsers.

### HTML Safety

- Repeated from Section 9: **never `.html_safe` on user input**. Use `sanitize` with an allowlist.

---

## Project Structure Rules

### Canonical Layout

- `app/controllers/concerns/` for shared controller mixins (authentication, authorization).
- `app/models/concerns/` for shared model mixins.
- `app/models/<model>/` for model-specific concerns (e.g. `app/models/user/authentication.rb`).
- `app/jobs/` for ActiveJob classes.
- `app/mailers/` for ActionMailer classes.
- `app/javascript/controllers/` for Stimulus controllers.
- `app/helpers/` -- keep minimal; prefer `tag.` helpers inline in views.
- `config/initializers/` -- one concern per file, kept small.
- `config/recurring.yml` for scheduled Solid Queue jobs.
- `config/deploy.yml` for Kamal.
- `test/controllers/`, `test/models/`, `test/system/`, `test/fixtures/` for test organization.
- `bin/setup`, `bin/dev`, `bin/ci`, `bin/rubocop`, `bin/brakeman` for developer scripts.

### What Does Not Belong

- **No `app/services/`** by default. Business logic belongs on models and model concerns. Add a service object only when the logic genuinely crosses multiple aggregate roots.
- **No `lib/` application logic.** `lib/` is for rake tasks, railties, and libraries that could be extracted to a gem. If it imports application models, it belongs in `app/`.
- **No god-initializers.** If an initializer exceeds 50 lines, split it.

### Naming

- Stimulus controllers: `<name>_controller.js` (snake_case file, auto-registered as `name`).
- Model concerns: `<Model>::<Concern>` module name, nested file path `app/models/<model>/<concern>.rb`.
- Rake tasks: `lib/tasks/<namespace>.rake`.

---

## Testing Rules

### Minitest and Fixtures

- **Minitest** is the default testing framework. Ships with Rails, fast, no DSL. RSpec is acceptable on existing projects (see Section 20).
- **Fixtures** are the default for test data. Deterministic ids, real schema, load once per suite. FactoryBot is acceptable on existing projects.

### Assertions

- `assert_difference -> { Post.count }, +1 do ... end` for state changes.
- `assert_enqueued_with(job: NotifyJob, args: [post])` for jobs.
- `assert_changes -> { post.published_at }, from: nil` for attribute mutation.
- `assert_no_difference` / `assert_no_changes` when verifying nothing happened.

### System Tests

- Capybara-driven browser tests in `test/system/`.
- Use role and label-based queries (`click_on "Publish"`, `fill_in "Title", with: "..."`), not CSS selectors.
- Test the critical user path; system tests are slow, so be selective.

### Parallel Tests

- Enable in `test/test_helper.rb`: `parallelize(workers: :number_of_processors)`.

### What NOT to Test

- Don't test Rails framework behavior (callbacks fire, validations run, routes route).
- Don't test trivial getters/setters.
- Don't test implementation details: internal instance variables, private methods, specific SQL.

### VCR for External HTTP

- Record external API responses with `vcr`. Cassettes in `test/vcr_cassettes/`.

---

## Tooling Rules

### Linting

- `rubocop-rails-omakase` is the blessed ruleset. No custom `.rubocop.yml`.
- Run via `bin/rubocop`.

### Security Scanning

- `brakeman` for Rails vulnerability scanning: `bin/brakeman`.
- `bundler-audit` for gem CVEs.
- `bin/importmap audit` for JavaScript dependency CVEs.

### CI Script

- `bin/ci` runs the full gate: rubocop, bundler-audit, importmap audit, brakeman, `bin/rails test`, `bin/rails test:system`. Mirror in your CI pipeline.

### Development Server

- `bin/dev` runs Puma and Solid Queue together via Procfile.dev.

---

## Migrations and Database Rules

### Reversible Migrations

- Use the `change` method for automatic reversibility.
- When you must write `up` / `down`, write both halves.

### Zero-Downtime Patterns

- **Adding a column**: add with a default, deploy, backfill if needed, deploy.
- **Removing a column**: stop using it in code (deploy), then remove the column (deploy).
- **Renaming a column**: add the new column, backfill, stop using old, then remove.
- **Large table index**: `add_index :table, :col, algorithm: :concurrently` (Postgres). Requires `disable_ddl_transaction!`.

### Foreign Keys and Constraints

- Always `foreign_key: true` on `references` columns.
- `null: false` and `default:` on columns where the business rule is "must always be set".
- `t.timestamps` on every table.

### UUID Primary Keys (Optional)

- Consider UUIDv7 when ids will be exposed in URLs, synced across systems, or generated outside the database.
- Default integer primary keys are fine for most apps. Don't switch without a reason.

---

## Rails 8+ Features and Deployment

### The Solid Trio

- **Solid Queue** for background jobs. Database-backed, no Redis. Runs as a Puma plugin or standalone process.
- **Solid Cache** for `Rails.cache`. Database-backed, persistent across restarts.
- **Solid Cable** for ActionCable. Database-backed pub/sub.
- A Rails 8 app runs with just Rails and a database. No Redis, no Memcached, no external queue.

### Importmap and Propshaft

- **Importmap-rails** is the default JavaScript loader. Pin packages with `bin/importmap pin <package>`. No Webpack, no esbuild, no bundler step.
- **Propshaft** is the default asset pipeline (not Sprockets). Serves assets with a digest for cache busting.

### Kamal Deployment

- `kamal setup` to provision, `kamal deploy` to ship, `kamal rollback <version>` to revert.
- Configuration in `config/deploy.yml`. Zero-downtime rolling deploys with healthchecks.

### Health Checks and Browser Gate

- Rails 8 ships `/up` by default. Point your monitor at it.
- `allow_browser versions: :modern` in ApplicationController drops legacy browsers.

---

## Large Project Maintenance

- `bundle outdated` monthly. Bump one major version per PR. Read the changelog.
- Delete dead code. Git remembers. No commented-out blocks, no long-lived `deprecated_` prefixes.
- Refactor only when asked or required for the task. Never mix a refactor with a feature.
- Document canonical patterns in this file so Claude and new contributors converge.
- Prefer smaller alternatives. Rails' omakase stack already ships most of what apps need:

| Instead of | Use | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| Devise | `bin/rails generate authentication` | Built-in, ~200 lines, no dependency |
| Sidekiq | Solid Queue | DB-backed, no Redis, runs in Puma |
| Redis (cache / cable) | Solid Cache / Solid Cable | Fewer services to run |
| Webpacker / esbuild-rails | Importmap + Propshaft | No bundler, faster dev loop |
| RSpec | Minitest | Ships with Rails, no DSL to learn |
| FactoryBot | Fixtures | Faster, deterministic, real schema |
| Pundit / CanCanCan | Model permission methods | Plain Ruby, testable, no gem |
| Service objects | Concerns + rich models | Rails-idiomatic, fewer indirections |
| `whenever` (cron DSL) | `config/recurring.yml` | Solid Queue's native scheduler |

---

## When Creating a New Rails Project

1. `rails new myapp --database=postgresql` (or `--database=sqlite3` for small self-hosted apps).
2. `bin/rails generate authentication` -- scaffolds `User`, `Session`, `PasswordsController`.
3. Add `allow_browser versions: :modern` to `ApplicationController`.
4. Configure `config/initializers/content_security_policy.rb` with an explicit allowlist.
5. Edit credentials (`bin/rails credentials:edit`), add required secrets. Never commit `master.key`.
6. Configure `config/deploy.yml` for Kamal.
7. Write `bin/ci` (rubocop + brakeman + bundler-audit + importmap audit + test + test:system).
8. Add `config/recurring.yml` with any scheduled jobs.
9. Configure Solid Queue in-puma for small deployments: `plugin :solid_queue` in `config/puma.rb`.
10. Create `Current` attributes class at `app/models/current.rb`.
11. Write a system test covering the critical path (sign in, create resource, see it render).
12. Set up `bin/setup` for fresh developer bootstrap.
13. Enable strict loading in development: `config.active_record.strict_loading_by_default = true`.
14. Commit `.env.example` if you use env vars for non-secret config. Never commit `.env`.

---

## When Working on an Existing Rails Project

1. Read the relevant files first. Understand existing patterns before writing.
2. **Follow existing conventions even when they diverge from this template.** If the project uses RSpec, write RSpec. If it uses FactoryBot, use FactoryBot. If it uses Devise, use Devise. If it has `app/services/`, add your new class there.
3. This is the centralized escape hatch for every "DHH default" in sections 3-19. Consistency with the surrounding code beats alignment with this template.
4. Do not refactor unrelated code. Do not mix refactors with features.
5. Do not introduce new gems or patterns without approval.
6. Match existing naming, organization, and style. When in doubt, copy the nearest neighbor.

---

## Checklist Before Completing Any Task

- [ ] `bin/rubocop` passes (omakase ruleset, no overrides)
- [ ] `bin/brakeman` clean
- [ ] `bundle exec bundler-audit` clean
- [ ] `bin/importmap audit` clean (if the project uses importmap)
- [ ] `bin/rails test` passes
- [ ] `bin/rails test:system` passes (if system tests exist)
- [ ] No N+1 queries introduced (spot-check the dev log, or enable strict loading)
- [ ] Strong params used for every create/update action
- [ ] No `.html_safe` on user input anywhere in the diff
- [ ] All callbacks use lambda syntax (`after_save -> { ... }`, never `after_save :method`)
- [ ] All async callbacks use `*_commit` variants (`after_create_commit`, never plain `after_create` for jobs/HTTP/broadcasts)
- [ ] Migrations reversible (`change` method, or matching `up`/`down`)
- [ ] No hardcoded secrets, API keys, or URLs -- use `Rails.application.credentials` or env vars
- [ ] New indexes added for any new column you filter or sort by
- [ ] No CI/CD pipeline files modified without explicit approval
- [ ] New gems justified (checked with `bundler-audit`, no smaller alternative, fits the omakase philosophy)

